TY  - JOUR
AU  - Baum-Snow, Nathaniel
T1  - Did Highways Cause Suburbanization?*
PY  - 2007
Y1  - 2007/05/01
DO  - 10.1162/qjec.122.2.775
JO  - The Quarterly Journal of Economics
JA  - Q J Econ
VL  - 122
IS  - 2
SP  - 775
EP  - 805
SN  - 0033-5533
AB  - Between 1950 and 1990, the aggregate population of central cities in the United States declined by 17 percent despite population growth of 72 percent in metropolitan areas as a whole. This paper assesses the extent to which the construction of new limited access highways has contributed to central city population decline. Using planned portions of the interstate highway system as a source of exogenous variation, empirical estimates indicate that one new highway passing through a central city reduces its population by about 18 percent. Estimates imply that aggregate central city population would have grown by about 8 percent had the interstate highway system not been built.
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1162/qjec.122.2.775
ER  - 



