TY  - JOUR
AU  - Echenique, Federico
AU  - Fryer, Roland G., Jr.
T1  - A Measure of Segregation Based on Social Interactions*
PY  - 2007
Y1  - 2007/05/01
DO  - 10.1162/qjec.122.2.441
JO  - The Quarterly Journal of Economics
JA  - Q J Econ
VL  - 122
IS  - 2
SP  - 441
EP  - 485
SN  - 0033-5533
AB  - We develop an index of segregation based on two premises: (1) a measure of segregation should disaggregate to the level of individuals, and (2) an individual is more segregated the more segregated are the agents with whom she interacts. We present an index that satisfies (1) and (2) and that is based on agents' social interactions: the extent to which blacks interact with blacks, whites with whites, etc. We use the index to measure school and residential segregation. Using detailed data on friendship networks, we calculate levels of within-school racial segregation in a sample of U. S. schools. We also calculate residential segregation across major U. S. cities, using block-level data from the 2000 U. S. Census.
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1162/qjec.122.2.441
ER  - 



